Memecoins

Systematic Memecoin Investing
Dustin Teander

6 hours ago ⋅  6 min read

This report was originally published as an Enterprise tier report on March 27, 2024.

Key Insights

  • Memecoin explosions typically occur after a measurable upswing in larger assets such as smart contract platforms.
  • Due to their role at the far end of the speculative risk curve, market drawdowns occur earlier in memecoins, thus acting as a signal to the broader market.
  • Knowing these fairly predictable role memecoins play in crypto cycles, one can encode a simple heuristic-based memecoin investing strategy that outreturns a market-cap-weighted basket of smart contract platforms by a factor of 28, or, if optimizing for memecoin investments on a velocity-weighted-bases, by a factor of 87.

Memecoins have historically been seen as a joke asset favored almost exclusively by retail and far out on the speculation curve beyond sensibility even for most crypto funds.

And that would be true. The volatility, lack of “fundamentals,” and general unseriousness are notoriously offputting for anyone with a semblance of fiduciary duty.

However, that does not preclude memecoins from an actual investment strategy.

Credible people have made arguments such as “memecoins are long-tail prediction markets” or “memecoins are continuous attention speculation vehicles” to justify why memecoins, the currently hot asset, are legitimate considerations. While there is some truth to these intellectualized framings, we will spare you their obtuse arguments for the simplicity of math and measurable correlations.

Memecoins, because of their fairly predictable role as the later-stage speculative asset in crypto, have a loose correlation with the larger, more “legit” assets that, on a historical basis, could have been gamed.

Historical Correlations

Crypto bull markets are often led by BTC or smart contract platforms for a variety of reasons (liquidity backdrop, risk-reward profiles, buyer persona, tech breakthroughs, etc). The appreciation of these “legit” assets acts as a social signal that “crypto isn’t dead” and, thus, kick-starting a wave of attention for both speculation and building. Speculation tends to flow down the risk curve until memecoins reach cultural relevance resulting in volcanic returns leaving investors in the “legit” assets in disbelief (DOGE went from under a billion market cap to nearly $90 billion in less than a hundred days from late January 2021 to early May).

However, as the assets at the furthest end of the risk spectrum, memecoins are typically one of the first asset sectors in crypto to see the speculative fire extinguished with volatile drawdowns. These typically signal the end of a broader speculative cessation and drawdown in cryptoassets (highlighted in red above).

In summary, the general trend is that infrastructure asset upswings coming out of bear market periods precede memecoin explosions, which inevitably crash, signaling the end of a speculative wave across all crypto assets resulting in broader downswings.

Given the more explosive returns of memecoins and the consistency of cascading trend cycle to cycle, the question arises: why not ignore “legit” investments and concentrate on memecoins once a broader upswing is identified?

Codifying Memecoin Investments

Observing the general trends highlighted above, one can codify them into a heuristic-based investment strategy that follows the general rules:

  • Smart Contract Rise: when in cash and the smart contract network market cap moving average rises above a threshold, allocate 90% of the portfolio to a market-cap-weighted basket of memecoins, 10% in smart contracts also market-cap-weighted.
  • Memecoin Rise: when the aggregate memecoin market cap eclipses a moving average threshold, move the entire portfolio to the memecoin basket.
  • Memecoin Crash: when memecoins experience a decline on a moving average basis beyond a threshold, move the entire portfolio to cash and freeze trading for a set number of days.
  • Cash Protection: if either smart contract networks or memecoins experience a near-term decline beyond a certain, larger threshold, move the entire portfolio to cash to manage risk.

Using a simple hand determination of the above thresholds, one can illustrate how this rather crude, entirely memecoin-driven strategy outperforms a buy-and-hold strategy of a market-cap-weighted basket of smart contract networks and memecoins from January 1, 2021, to March 24, 2024. Comparatively, the memecoin strategy returns 13,877% (138x), memecoins 7897%, and smart contract networks 494%.

Building off of Ally’s work in “Navigating Memecoin Mania,” one could further optimize the strategy to allocate the memecoin portion of the portfolio on a velocity-weighted basis rather than a market-cap-weighted basis since DOGE and SHIB so heavily dominate market caps and new coins are where the majority of returns are. For liquidity reasons, the strategy would only invest in top memecoins above a $200 million market cap at the time of allocation. The result magnifies the gains to over 43,000% across the same period.

(Please note, in addition to the disclaimers at the end of this report, this does not in any way constitute investment advice to buy or sell any assets and is merely an illustrative look at how memecoin returns compare to more established assets on a historical if one follows basic risk management practices.)

Observations and Risks

While the backtest of the simple strategy produced far higher returns than aggregate smart contract platforms and memecoins, it does not mean the trend will continue in large part because memecoins have become much more popular and understood.

In 2021, where a significant portion of the strategy’s returns were, memecoins were misunderstood and almost consensusly ignored. As that worldview dissolved away, memecoins have become consistent characters with fairly predictable behaviors. People now rush to buy memecoins almost immediately once price activity picks up which has significantly collapsed the correlative period of broader market price increases preceding memecoin purchases. Effectively, the market understands the game. This erodes much of the predictive behavior leaving memecoins largely as highly speculative (and fun) bets on market attention.

Conclusion

Memecoins have historically played a fairly predictable role in crypto cycles as the rather unserious, later-stage speculative asset characterized by explosive returns and equally explosive drawdowns. This leads some people to regard memecoins with contempt or an air of superiority. However, with the benefit of hindsight, the optimal strategy, from a returns perspective, would be to harness the winds rather than justify lower returns with moral rectitude.

By encoding a simple heuristic model for investing in memecoins drawing upon their now recurring role in crypto markets as long-tail risk assets arising later in market cycles, one can illustrate returns that out-return a market-cap-weighted basket of smart contract platforms by a factor of 28 or 87 if memecoin investments are done on velocity-weighted bases.

However, because the role memecoins play in the markets has become so well understood, the correlations and predictive behaviors of a simple heuristic model have begun to erode in a serious way. Memecoins are now highly competitive as people rush to buy them earlier in cycles (almost immediately nowadays) and at near rock bottom valuations effectively betting that the same patterns of previous cycles play out.

So, while one can illustrate the superior returns of systematically investing in memecoins in the past, the market has adapted in some respects. This results in attention and capital being fractured among many memecoins and an overall compression on returns taking into account the risk-reward profile of the aggregate set of memecoins (there, of course, will still be significant returns in select memecoins and for people with a pulse on cultural attention).
